ks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  . This surname is now rare in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbett","meanings":["English (West Midlands, of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>corbet</i> ‘raven’, probably denoting someone with dark hair or a dark complexion.","History: This is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."]}]},{"name":"Eléonore","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Provençal.  See  <b>Eleanor</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eléonore de Corbie was born in 1164, in Corbie, Somme, Picardie, France, her father, Arthur de Corbie, was 38 and her mother, Mathilde de Contay, was 25. She married Louis de Roucy. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1208, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1164–1208":"1164–1208","1156–1213":"1156–1213","1157–1209":"1157–1209","1160–1214":"1160–1214","1161–1229":"1161–1229","1188–1228":"1188–1228","1126–1184":"1126–1184","1139–1187":"1139–1187","1187":"1187","1164":"1164","1184":"1184","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1228":"1228","1139":"1139","1126":"1126","1214":"1214","1213":"1213","1157":"1157","1156":"1156","1188":"1188","1209":"1209","1208":"1208","1229":"1229","Montdidier, Somme, Picardie, France":"Montdidier, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Corbie, Somme, Picardie, França":"Corbie, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1164–1208":"1164–1208","1156–1213":"1156–1213","1157–1209":"1157–1209","1160–1214":"1160–1214","1161–1229":"1161–1229","1188–1228":"1188